<TITLE> London Scottish says can't sustain business model </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Feb 26 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Britain's London Scottish Bank, which lends to lower-income consumers, said on Tuesday its current business model was no longer sustainable because of the credit crisis and it would reduce lending and sell assets. London Scottish posted a bigger-than-expected full-year loss and announced it had agreed a plan with the Financial Services Authority (FSA) to scale back lending to solve a 12.7 million pounds ($25 million) regulatory capital shortfall as of Jan. 1. London Scottish had earlier racked up losses meaning it did not have enough money in reserve relative to its lending, breaching FSA rules. London Scottish said it would restructure its business around its debt collection arm, Robinson Way, whose profits rose 57 percent to 13.9 million pounds in the year to Oct. 31, 2007. Analysts had expected the firm to raise money to fund future lending by an asset sale or issuing more shares. The group posted full-year results showing a pretax loss, including discontinued operations, of 15.7 million pounds versus a Reuters estimate of 11 million pounds, according to three analysts. The loss on continuing operations was 18.1 million pounds for the peri
